{{Europe-mag-stub}}

{{good article}}
[[File:Bixby Letter newspaper.jpg|thumb|260px|The Bixby letter in the ''Boston Evening Transcript'']]
The '''Bixby letter''' is a brief, consoling message sent by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] in November 1864 to Lydia Parker Bixby, a widow living in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], who was thought to have lost five sons in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. Along with the [[Gettysburg Address]] and his [[Lincoln's second inaugural address|second inaugural address]], the letter has been praised as one of Lincoln's finest written works and is often reproduced in memorials, media, and print.

Controversy surrounds the recipient, the fate of her sons, and the authorship of the letter. Bixby's character has been questioned (including rumored [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] sympathies), at least two of her sons survived the war, and the letter was possibly written by Lincoln's assistant private secretary, [[John Hay]].

==Text==
[[File:Abraham Lincoln November 1863.jpg|thumb|right|Abraham Lincoln, the 16th President of the United States]]
President Lincoln's letter of condolence was delivered to Lydia Bixby on November 25, 1864 and was printed in the ''[[Boston Evening Transcript]]'' and ''[[Boston Evening Traveller]]'' that afternoon.<ref name="Transcript">{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=sArNgO4T4MoC&dat=18641125&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Letter from President Lincoln|last=|first=|date=25 November 1864|work=[[Boston Evening Transcript]]|volume=|page=2|access-date=6 April 2016|via=Google Newspapers}}</ref><ref name="Traveller">{{Cite news|url=|title=[[c:File:Bixby Letter Boston Evening Traveller.jpg|A Mother in Israel - Five of Her Sons Killed during the War - A Sixth Severely Wounded - President Lincoln Sends her the Thanks of the Republic]]|last=|first=|date=25 November 1864|work=[[Boston Evening Traveller]]|newspaper=|edition=2nd|page=2|access-date=|via=}}</ref>{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/50/mode/2up 50&ndash;51]}} The following is the text of the letter as first published:{{efn|The ''Transcript'' wrote the letter's date as "Nov. 21, 1864" while the ''Traveller'' wrote it as "21st November, 1864".<ref name="Traveller" />}}<ref name="Transcript" />

{{quote |
Executive Mansion,<br/>
Washington, Nov. 21, 1864.

Dear Madam,

I have been shown in the files of the War Department a statement of the Adjutant General of Massachusetts that you are the mother of five sons who have died gloriously on the field of battle.

I feel how weak and fruitless must be any words of mine which should attempt to beguile you from the grief of a loss so overwhelming. But I cannot refrain from tendering to you the consolation that may be found in the thanks of the Republic they died to save.

I pray that our Heavenly Father may assuage the anguish of your bereavement, and leave you only the cherished memory of the loved and lost, and the solemn pride that must be yours to have laid so costly a sacrifice upon the altar of Freedom.

Yours, very sincerely and respectfully,<br/>
A. Lincoln.

Mrs. Bixby.}}

==History==
[[File:William Schouler.jpg|thumb|right|210px|William Schouler, Massachusetts Adjutant General]]
Lydia Parker married shoemaker Cromwell Bixby on September 26, 1826, in [[Hopkinton, Massachusetts]]. The couple had at least six sons and three daughters before Cromwell's death in 1854. Some time before the Civil War, Bixby and her family settled in Boston.{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|pp=387&ndash;389}}

===Meeting with Adjutant General Schouler===
On September 24, 1864, [[Massachusetts Adjutant General]] [[William Schouler]] wrote to [[Massachusetts Governor]] [[John Albion Andrew]] about a [[Military discharge|discharge]] request sent to the governor by Otis Newhall, the father of five [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] soldiers. In the letter, Schouler recalled how, two years prior, they had helped a poor widow named Lydia Bixby to visit a son who was a patient at an Army hospital. About ten days earlier, Bixby had come to Schouler's office claiming that five of her sons had died fighting for the Union. Governor Andrew forwarded Newhall's request to the [[United States Department of War|U.S. War Department]] with a note requesting that the president honor Bixby with a letter.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/14/mode/2up 13&ndash;17]}}

In response to a War Department request of October 1, Schouler sent a messenger to Bixby's home six days later, asking for the names and units of her sons. He sent a report to the War Department on October 12, which was delivered to President Lincoln by [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Edwin Stanton]] sometime after October 28.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/18/mode/2up 18&ndash;21]}}{{sfn|Steers|Holzer|2007|pp=94&ndash;95}}

On November 21, both the ''Boston Evening Traveller'' and the ''Boston Evening Transcript'' published an appeal by Schouler for contributions to assist soldiers' families at [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] which mentioned a widow who had lost five sons in the war.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=[[c:File:Schouler Thanksgiving appeal.jpg|Thanksgiving Day - An Appeal in Behalf of Soldiers' Families]]|last=|first=|date=21 November 1864|work=[[Boston Evening Traveller]]|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=2}}</ref>{{sfn|Barton|1926|pp=40-43}} Schouler had some of the donations given to Bixby and then visited her home on Thanksgiving, November 24. The letter from the President arrived at Schouler's office the next morning.<ref name="Traveller" />{{sfn|Bullard|1946|p=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/46/mode/2up 46]}}

===Military record of the Bixby sons===
[[File:Lydia Bixby affidavit (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|210px|Bixby's 1862 affidavit attempting to secure a discharge for son Edward]]
Nevertheless, at least two of Lydia Bixby's sons survived the war:
* Private Arthur Edward Bixby (known as "Edward") – Company C, [[1st Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Heavy Artillery|1st Massachusetts Heavy Artillery]] (enlisted June 24, 1861). Deserted from [[Fort Richardson (Arlington, Virginia)|Ft. Richardson]], [[Virginia]] on May 28, 1862.<ref name="MSSMv5">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/massachusettssol51931mass#page/576/mode/2up|title=Massachusetts Soldiers, Sailors, and Marines in the Civil War: Volume V|last=Massachusetts Adjutant General Office|first=|publisher=Norwood Press|year=1932|isbn=|location=Norwood, Massachusetts|pages=22, 576}}</ref> Trying to secure a discharge for him, his mother filed an affidavit on October 17, 1862 which claimed Edward had enlisted underage without her permission.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/32/mode/2up 32&ndash;34]}} Born July 13, 1843 in Hopkinton, Massachusetts. Returned to Boston after the war.{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|p=388}}
* Sergeant Charles N. Bixby – Company D, [[20th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|20th Massachusetts Infantry]] (served July 18, 1861 – May 3, 1863). Killed in action near [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]]. Born c.1841 in Hopkinton, Massachusetts.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|p=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/28/mode/2up 29]}}<ref name="MSSMv2">{{Cite book|title = Massachusetts Soldiers, Sailors and Marines in the Civil War: Volume II|last = Massachusetts Adjutant General Office|first = |publisher = Norwood Press|year = 1931|isbn = |location = Norwood, Massachusetts|pages = 523, 549|url = https://archive.org/stream/massachusettssol21931mass#page/n531/mode/2up|volume = }}</ref>
* Corporal Henry Cromwell Bixby – 1st enlistment, Company G, 20th Massachusetts Infantry (served July 18, 1861 – May 29, 1862).{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|p=[https://archive.org/stream/genealogyofdesce00bixb#page/n465/mode/2up 392]}}<ref name="MSSMv2" /> 2nd enlistment, Company K, [[32nd Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|32nd Massachusetts Infantry]] (served August 5, 1862 – December 17, 1864). Captured at [[Battle of Gettysburg|Gettysburg]] and sent to [[Richmond, Virginia]]. [[Parole#Prisoners of war|Paroled]] on March 7, 1864 at [[City Point, Virginia]].{{sfn|Bullard|1946|p=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/28/mode/2up 29]}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/massachusettssol31931mass#page/520/mode/2up|title=Massachusetts Soldiers and Sailors in the Civil War: Volume III|last=Massachusetts Adjutant General Office|first=|publisher=Norwood Press|year=1932|isbn=|location=Norwood, Massachusetts|pages=520}}</ref> Born March 30, 1830 in Hopkinton, Massachusetts. Died November 8, 1871 in [[Milford, Massachusetts]],{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|p=387}} from [[tuberculosis]] he contracted while a soldier.{{sfn|Nieters|2018}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=[[c:File:Lydia Bixby 1874 charity appeal.jpg|A Case of Destitution]]|last=|first=|date=4 April 1874|work=[[Boston Daily Globe]]|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>
* Private Oliver Cromwell Bixby, Jr. – Company E, 58th Massachusetts Infantry (served February 26, 1864 – July 30, 1864). Wounded at [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House|Spotsylvania]] on May 12, 1864. Killed in action near [[Siege of Petersburg|Petersburg, Virginia]]. Born February 1, 1828 in Hopkinton, Massachusetts.{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|p=387}}<ref name="MSSMv5" />
* Private George Way Bixby – Company B, 56th Massachusetts Infantry (served March 16, 1864 – ?). Enlisted under the name "George Way," apparently to conceal his enlistment from his wife. Captured at Petersburg on July 30, 1864. First held prisoner at Richmond but later transferred to [[Salisbury Prison]] in [[North Carolina]], arriving there on October 9, 1864. His fate after that remains uncertain. Military records report conflicting accounts of him either dying at Salisbury or deserting to the Confederate Army.{{efn|A "George Bixby, nephew of Cuba" is also mentioned in an 1878 estate record of Albert Bixby, an uncle who died in Milford, Massachusetts.{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|p=388}} However, this George was not included on the estate's list of surviving heirs of Cromwell Bixby. Milford relatives later admitted confusing Lydia Bixby's sons with cousins having the same name.{{sfn|Banning|1922|p=519}}}}{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/28/mode/2up 28&ndash;32]}}{{sfn|Steers|Holzer|2007|p=97}} Born June 22, 1836 in Hopkinton, Massachusetts.{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|p=388}}

Schouler's report to the War Department erroneously listed Edward as a member of the [[22nd Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|22nd Massachusetts Infantry]] who had died of his wounds at [[Folly Island]], [[South Carolina]].{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/32/mode/2up 32&ndash;33]}}<ref name="Traveller" /> Bixby may have been trying to conceal—possibly from embarrassment or hope of further financial aid—Edward's 1862 desertion. (She had been receiving a pension following Charles's death in 1863.){{sfn|Bullard|1946|p=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/22/mode/2up 22]}}

At the time of her September meeting with Schouler, Bixby's son George had been a prisoner of war for just over a month, and Henry was still hospitalized following his exchange.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/46/mode/2up 46&ndash;47]}}  The War Department failed to use its own records to correct errors in the Schouler report.{{sfn|Steers|Holzer|2007|pp=95&ndash;97}}

===Questions of character===
Lydia Bixby died in Boston on October 27, 1878, while a patient at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]]. In his initial letter to Governor Andrew, Schouler called Bixby "the best specimen of a true-hearted Union woman I have yet seen,"{{sfn|Bullard|1946|p=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/16/mode/2up 16]}} but in the years following her death both her character and loyalty were questioned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2014/11/28/defense-boston-widow-bixby/1iiMKXLf27SEr8toEhRy8N/story.html|title=In defense of Boston's Widow Bixby|last=Giesberg|first=Judith|date=28 November 2014|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|access-date=11 January 2016|via=}}</ref>{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/48/mode/2up 48&ndash;49]}}

Writing to her daughter in 1904, Boston socialite Sarah Cabot Wheelwright claimed she had met and had given charitable aid to Lydia Bixby during the war, hoping that one of her sons, in Boston on leave, might help deliver packages to Union prisoners of war; but she later heard gossip that Bixby "kept a [[Brothel|house of ill-fame]], was perfectly untrustworthy and as bad as she could be".{{sfn|Burlingame|1995|pp=60&ndash;61}}{{sfn|Shattuck|1963}}

In the 1920s, Lincoln scholar, William E Barton interviewed the oldest residents of Hopkinton, Massachusetts for their memories of Bixby's family before she moved to Boston. They recalled her sons as being "tough" with "some of them too fond of drink". One son may have "served a jail sentence for some misdemeanor".{{sfn|Barton|1926|pp=79&ndash;80}}

On August 12, 1925, Elizabeth Towers, a daughter of Oliver Bixby, told the ''[[Boston Herald]]'' that her grandmother had "great sympathy for the South" and that her mother recalled that Bixby had been "highly indignant" about the letter with "little good to say of President Lincoln".{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/44/mode/2up 45]}}<ref name="Towers">{{Cite news|url=|title=MRS. BIXBY TORE UP LINCOLN NOTE KIN BELIEVES Heart in Southern Cause, Her Granddaughter Declares EMBITTERED, TOO, BY DEATH OF SONS President's Error May Have Angered Her, Lawrence Woman Avers|last=|first=|date=12 August 1925|work=|newspaper=[[The Boston Herald]]|edition=Morning|page=1|access-date=|via=}}</ref> In 1949, Towers' nephew, Arthur March Bixby, claimed that Lydia Bixby had moved to Massachusetts from [[Richmond, Virginia]];{{sfn|Burlingame|1995|pp=60, n8}} though this assertion is contradicted by contemporary records that list her birthplace as [[Rhode Island]].{{efn|Lydia Bixby's own 1878 death record listed her birthplace as Hopkinton, Massachusetts, but census records and death records of surviving children listed her birthplace as Rhode Island.{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|pp=387&ndash;389}}}}{{sfn|Bixby|Putnam|1914|pp=387&ndash;389}}

==Copies==

===The original===
[[File:Esther Stockton letter.jpg|thumb|200px|Lincoln sent a similar letter to Esther Stockton in January 1864, thanking her for knitting 300 pairs of socks for Union soldiers.]]
The fate of the original letter given to Bixby is unknown. William A. Bixby, a son of Oliver, told ''[[The New York Times]]'' in an August 9, 1925 interview that he did not know what happened to the letter after his grandmother received it, though he doubted it still survived.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/08/09/archives/grandson-believes-bixby-letter-lost-declares-his-grandmother-would.html|title=GRANDSON BELIEVES BIXBY LETTER LOST; Declares His Grandmother Would Not Realize the Value of Lincoln's Message. RELATIVES ARE UNCERTAIN But One Says He Is Sure Five of Mrs. Bixby's Sons Were Killed.|last=|first=|date=9 August 1925|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=11 December 2015|via=}}</ref> A few days later, William's sister, Elizabeth told the ''Boston Herald'' that she also did not know the letter's fate but speculated Bixby may have torn it up, resenting that it incorrectly said five of her sons had been killed.<ref name="Towers" /> William's son, Arthur March Bixby, told the ''[[The Sun (New York)|New York Sun]]'' in 1949 that he recalled his father telling him that she had angrily destroyed the letter after receiving it.{{sfn|Burlingame|1995|p=60}}<ref name="Burlingame">{{cite journal|last=Burlingame|first=Michael|date=July–August 1999|title=The Trouble With the Bixby Letter|url=https://www.americanheritage.com/content/trouble-bixby-letter|journal=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]]|volume=50|issue=4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160214152230/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/trouble-bixby-letter?page=show|archive-date=14 February 2016}}</ref>

In the early 20th century, it was sometimes claimed that the original letter could be found on display at [[Brasenose College]] at the [[University of Oxford]] along with other great works in the [[English language]]. Lincoln scholar [[F. Lauriston Bullard]] investigated this claim in 1925, discovering that it was untrue and the college had never heard of the Bixby letter.<ref name="Peterson">{{cite book |last=Peterson|first=Merrill D. |title=Lincoln in American Memory|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] US|year=1995|pages=246|chapter=Ch. 5 Themes and Variations|isbn=0-19-509645-2 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=D_FjY_ARcGoC&pg=PA246 |accessdate=2009-07-13}}</ref>

===Tobin facsimile===
[[File:Bixby Letter (Tobin facsimile).jpg|thumb|200px|Michael F. Tobin's 1891 lithographic facsimile of the letter]]
[[File:Bixby letter facsimile.jpg|thumb|200px|Huber's Museum sold these copies of Tobin's facsimile.]]
[[Christie's]] auction house receives many supposed original Bixby letters every year,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/02/11/lincoln-bicentennial-gettysburg-lifestyle-collecting_0211_lincoln.html |title=Lincoln's Lost Memorabilia |work=Forbes |author=Burke, Monte |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=October 4, 2010}}</ref> including copies of a lithographic facsimile of the letter in widespread circulation. These first appeared in 1891, when [[New York City]] print dealer Michael F. Tobin applied for a [[copyright]] to sell souvenir copies of the letter with an engraving of Lincoln by [[John Chester Buttre]] for $2 each.{{sfn|Steers|Holzer|2007|pp=96, 98}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/2003653265/|title=Letter from Abraham Lincoln to Mrs. Bixby, with bust-length portrait of Lincoln|last=|first=|date=|website=Library of Congress|publisher=|access-date=26 July 2016}}</ref> Soon, Huber's Museum, a [[dime museum]] in [[Manhattan]], began displaying a copy, "stained by coffee and exposure", of Tobin's facsimile as "the original Bixby letter" and selling their own copies for $1 each.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/54/mode/2up 54&ndash;58]}}{{sfn|Banning|1922|p=520}}

[[Charles Hamilton (handwriting expert)|Charles Hamilton]], an [[autograph]] dealer and handwriting expert, examined the Tobin facsimile; concluding it had been copied from a poorly executed [[forgery]] originally written in pencil and retraced in ink to imitate Lincoln's handwriting, calling it "halting and awkward and makes his forceful hand appear like a child's scrawl".<ref>{{Cite book|title = Great Forgers and Famous Fakes|last = Hamilton|first = Charles|publisher = Crown Publishers|year = 1980|isbn = |location = New York|pages = 29–37}}</ref>

Tobin's facsimile also errs when compared to the original text of the letter published in Boston newspapers; adding the [[salutation]] "To Mrs Bixby, Boston Mass", misspelling the word "assuage" as "assauge", omitting the word "to" after the word "tendering", changing the plural "words" into "word", not capitalizing the words "freedom" and "republic", missing the recipient "Mrs. Bixby" on the bottom left, and combining the original three paragraphs into one.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/146/mode/2up 146&ndash;147]}}<ref name="Basler">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/collectedworksof015584mbp#page/n131/mode/2up|title=Abraham Lincoln to Mrs. Lydia Bixby|last=Basler|first=Roy P.|year=1953|work=Collected Works of Abraham Lincoln Vol. 8|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=New Brunswick, New Jersey|pages=116-117}}</ref> Huber's Museum corrected the spelling of "assuage" in their version of the facsimile.{{sfn|Emerson|2008|p=108}}
[[File:John Hay (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|178px|John Hay, Lincoln's private secretary]]

==Authorship==
Scholars have debated whether the Bixby letter was written by Lincoln himself or by his assistant [[Secretary to the President of the United States|private secretary]], [[John Hay]].<ref name="Emerson">{{cite journal|last=Emerson |first=Jason |date=February–March 2006 |title=America's Most Famous Letter |url=https://www.americanheritage.com/content/america%E2%80%99s-most-famous-letter |journal=[[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]] |volume=57 |issue=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401181131/http://www.americanheritage.com/content/america%E2%80%99s-most-famous-letter?page=show |archive-date= 1 April 2016 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> November 1864 was a busy month for Lincoln, possibly forcing him to delegate the task to Hay.<ref name="Burlingame" />

Second- and third-hand recollections of acquaintances suggest Hay may have claimed to others that he wrote it,{{sfn|Steers|Holzer|2007|pp=98-100}} but his children could not recall him ever mentioning composing the letter.{{sfn|Bullard|1946|p=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/108/mode/2up 109]}} Writing to [[William E. Chandler]] in 1904, Hay said "the letter of Mr. Lincoln to Mrs. Bixby is genuine",{{sfn|Bullard|1946|pp=[https://archive.org/stream/abrahamlincolnwi00bull#page/122/mode/2up 122&ndash;125]}} but he may only have been referring to its text.{{sfn|Burlingame|1995|p=69}} In a 1917 letter to historian [[Isaac Markens]], [[Robert Todd Lincoln]] said Hay had told him that he did not have "any special knowledge of the letter at the time" it was written.{{sfn|Emerson|2008|pp=104-106}}<ref>{{Cite book| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=tPqgC3RS-7sC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Bixby%20Hay&f=false | title = Giant in the Shadows: The Life of Robert T. Lincoln| last = Emerson |first = Jason| publisher = Southern Illinois University Press| year = 2012| isbn = | location = Carbondale, Illinois| pages = 376, 537}}</ref>

Historian [[Michael Burlingame (historian)|Michael Burlingame]], who believes Hay is the author, has pointed out that Hay's [[scrapbooking|scrapbooks]] have two newspaper clippings of the letter while largely containing Hay's own writing.{{sfn|Burlingame|1995|pp=70&ndash;71}} However, they also contain material written by Lincoln including the [[Gettysburg Address]] and the [[Abraham Lincoln's second inaugural address|Second Inaugural]].<ref name="Emerson" />

Scholars favoring Lincoln's authorship, including [[Edward Steers, Jr.|Edward Steers]] and Jason Emerson, note that the Gettysburg Address and the [[Abraham Lincoln's Farewell Address|Farewell Address]] are similar examples of Lincoln's highly regarded style.<ref name="Emerson"/>{{sfn|Steers|Holzer|2007|p=93}} Other scholars, such as Burlingame, have countered that Hay wrote pieces that compare favorably to the Bixby letter and note words and phrases in the letter that appear more frequently in Hay's writings than those of Lincoln.{{sfn|Burlingame|2000|pp=169&ndash;184}} For instance, Burlingame notes the word ''beguile'' appears numerous times in the works of Hay and the phrase ''I cannot refrain from tendering'' is used by Hay in an 1864 letter to [[Quincy Gillmore]], but neither appears once in the other collected works of Lincoln.{{sfn|Burlingame|2000|pp=86, 169&ndash;184}} Although, the phrase ''I cannot refrain from'' is used by Lincoln in an 1859 letter to [[Salmon P. Chase]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/l/lincoln/lincoln3/1:143?hi=0;rgn=div1;view=fulltext;q1=I+cannot+refrain+from|title=Letter to Salmon P. Chase, 21 Sept. 1859|work=Collected Works of Abraham Lincoln. Volume 3.|last=Basler|first=Roy P.|year=1953|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326190754/https://quod.lib.umich.edu/l/lincoln/lincoln3/1:143?hi=0;rgn=div1;view=fulltext;q1=I+cannot+refrain+from|archive-date=26 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=26 March 2018}}</ref>

In 1988, at the request of investigator [[Joe Nickell]], [[University of Kentucky]] professor of English Jean G. Pival studied the vocabulary, syntax, and other stylistic characteristics of the letter and concluded that it more closely resembled Lincoln's style of writing than Hay's.{{sfn|Nickell|1989|pp=137&ndash;140}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1V-BIdlc9YEC&pg=PA95|title=Unsolved History: Investigating Mysteries of the Past|last=Nickell|first=Joe|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|year=2005|isbn=978-0-8131-9137-9|pages=95–105, 164|chapter=Suspect Documents|accessdate=2009-07-14}}</ref> 
[[File:StatuePacificCemetery.png|thumb|200px|Inscription quoting the Bixby letter at the National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]]

==Legacy==
The letter's passage "the solemn pride that must be yours to have laid so costly a sacrifice upon the altar of freedom" is inscribed on the base of the statue of [[Columbia (name)#Personification|Lady Columbia]] at the [[National Memorial Cemetery of the Pacific]] in [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pacom.mil/Media/SpeechesTestimony/tabid/6706/Article/785134/67th-honolulu-mayors-memorial-day-ceremony.aspx|title=67th Honolulu Mayor’s Memorial Day Ceremony|date=31 May 2016|website=www.pacom.mil|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623000928/http://www.pacom.mil/Media/SpeechesTestimony/tabid/6706/Article/785134/67th-honolulu-mayors-memorial-day-ceremony.aspx|archive-date=23 June 2016|access-date=}}</ref>

Discussions on the topic of siblings dying in war have frequently mentioned the letter; such as the [[Sullivan brothers]], the [[Niland brothers]], the [[Borgstrom brothers]], and the [[Sole Survivor Policy]] of the [[United States military]].<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CAEyh6EY9kYC|title=Saving Private Property: Steven Spielberg's American DreamWorks|last=Kodat|first=Catherine Gunther|work=The American Experience in World War II|volume= 11: ''Remembering and Representing the Second World War''|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|isbn=|editor-last=Hixson|editor-first=Walter L.|location=New York|pages=255&ndash;256}}</ref>

In the 1998 war film ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'', General [[George Marshall]] (played by [[Harve Presnell]]) reads the Bixby letter to his officers before giving the order to find and send home Private James Francis Ryan after Ryan's three brothers died in battle. In a voiceover near the end of the film, Marshall quotes the Bixby letter in a letter to Mrs. Ryan.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_LycDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA194|title=The Progressive Revolution: History of Liberal Fascism through the Ages, Vol. V: 2014-2015 Writings|last=Washington|first=Ellis|publisher=Hamilton Books|year=2017|isbn=9780761868507|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=191-194|language=en}}</ref> 

On September 11, 2011, former U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] read the Bixby letter during the memorial ceremony at the [[World Trade Center site]] on the tenth anniversary of the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/12/us/12obama.html|title=Bush and Obama, Shoulder to Shoulder|date=September 11, 2011|last2=Schmitt|first2=Eric|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first1=Mark|last1=Landler}}</ref>

