{{Italic title}} '''''Broussard v. School Board of Norfolk''''', 801 F. Supp. 1526 ([[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia|E.D. Va.]] 1992) was a court case that took place in [[Norfolk, Virginia]], United States in 1992. Kimberly Broussard, a middle school student was disciplined by the [[Norfolk Public Schools]] for wearing a t-shirt that read "Drugs Suck". When her parents sued on her behalf, her lawyer claimed that her shirt was a form of [[Freedom of speech|free speech]] protected by the [[First Amendment of the United States Constitution]] and the [[Tinker v. Des Moines Independent Community School District|Tinker Standard]]. The [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia]] ruled in favor of the school board, saying that although the shirt displayed an anti-drug message, the word "suck" was a vulgar word with a sexual [[connotation]] and therefore not allowed in school.
==See also== *[[School speech (First Amendment)|School speech]] **''[[Guiles v. Marineau]]'': a similar case with student T-shirts **''[[Tinker v. Des Moines Independent Community School District]]'', 393 U.S. 503 (1969) **''[[Bethel School District v. Fraser]]'', 478 U.S. 675 (1986) **''[[Morse v. Frederick]]'', 551 U.S. 393 (2007) *[[Obscenity]] **''[[Cohen v. California]]'', 403 U.S. 15 (1971) **''[[Miller v. California]]'', 413 U.S. 15 (1973)
==External links== *[https://web.archive.org/web/20070305234459/http://www.nsba.org/site/docs/32600/32540.pdf The case mentioned as precedent in another case]
